The Deputy Permanent Secretary in Tamisemi (Health), Dr Zainab Chaula, gave the directive here yesterday, noting that OPRAS will enable the government assess the performance of all 650 public servants under the ministry by the end of this year. “OPRAS forms from public servants in all district and town councils should also be submitted to their heads of department by August 15,” said the Deputy Permanent Secretary - Health, while addressing Tamisemi staff during OPRAS Week. The focus of OPRAS Week, whose participants included the Deputy Permanent Secretary in President’s Office-Education, Mr Tixon Nzunda, is to raise awareness on the importance of OPRAS enhancing public service efficiency.